Read: 09 - Forms and Events

SUMMARY:

1.	Forms:
a.	<form> element is used to collect information from visitors.
b.	Information from a form is sent in name/value pairs.
c.	Each form control has a name and the user input, also known as values are sent to the server.
d.	HTML5 has new form elements which is much easier to fill in forms.


2.	Lists, Tables, and Forms:
a.	Forms can be styled.
b.	Alignment of form controls with CSS makes it easier to use forms.
c.	Different browsers can have different borders and spacing for table cells but we can control their properties to make them more consistent.
d.	list-style-type and list-style are image properties that we can use to give different appearance to the list markers.

3.	Events:
a.	Browsers indicate when something has happened, that is called event.
b.	The process of stating which event is about to happen is binding. And also, which element that event is to happen upon.
c.	JavaScript function is triggered by the event. This function then changes the web page in some way. It now feels interactive because it has responded to the user.
d.	Event delegation can be used to monitor for events that happen on all children of an element.
e.	W3C DOM events are the most commonly used events.
